cs.LO, cs.PL, cs.DC, cs.SE, cs.DS

This paper discusses the expressiveness of communication primitives in a common framework based on the π-calculus, which is a topic related to programming languages and formal methods. Therefore, the most likely sub-category is cs.LO (Logic in Computer Science). The paper also discusses the Join Calculus, which is a concurrent programming language, and the general rendezvous calculus, which is a model for distributed systems, suggesting that the paper could also belong to cs.PL (Programming Languages) and cs.DC (Distributed, Parallel, and Cluster Computing). Additionally, the paper discusses the features of communication primitives, which could be relevant to cs.SE (Software Engineering) and cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms).
